Even counting power covered by agreements in principle, the state will be=
=20
about 40 million megawatt-hours short of the 60 million megawatt-hours it=
=20
will need to buy this year for customers of California's nearly bankrupt=20
utilities, according to a report prepared by David Freeman, general manager=
=20
of the Los Angeles Department of Water and Power and the state's lead=20
negotiator on the deals, and obtained Wednesday by Dow Jones Newswires.=20
California will have to cover those megawatt-hours in the market, where the=
y=20
will be expensive, assuming they are available at all. The current forward=
=20
price of power for the balance of the year is about $325 a megawatt-hour,=
=20
which would put California's spot-market bill at $13 billion for the=20
remainder of the year. That figure is likely too low, however, because the=
=20
state will be far shorter in the summer, when demand and prices are much=20
higher, than in the winter. The forward price of power for delivery this=20
summer is now averaging about $480 a megawatt-hour. Moreover, the shortfall=
=20
could grow if some of the agreements in principle don't mature into actual=
=20
deals, Freeman wrote.=20
On March 5, Freeman said the state had lined up contracts to cover 60% to 7=
0%=20
of the state's "net short" position this summer. The net short position is=
=20
the difference between the power consumed by California's three largest=20
utilities and the power those utilities generate themselves or have under=
=20
contract. At that time, Freeman told Dow Jones Newswires that the summer=20
deals were only agreements in principle and not firm contracts. Freeman=20
wasn't immediately available Wednesday for comment.=20
In his March 15 report to DWR Director Ray Hart, Freeman says the DWR has=
=20
entered into 19 final power contracts, with seven suppliers, and more than =
25=20
agreements in principle. In 2001, the state's deals cover at most 6,502=20
megawatts at any given time. Of that, only 2,247 megawatts are covered by=
=20
signed contracts. Even that figure, however, is just an approximation, as=
=20
some power is contingent upon availability or the completion of power plant=
s=20
that might not be built in time, Freeman wrote.=20
Coverage for 2002 so far is also slim, according to Freeman's report. The=
=20
deals cover at most 7,500 megawatts at any given time, and the state will=
=20
still face an uncovered short position of about 40 million megawatt-hours.=
=20
California put itself in the power markets in mid-January, when the=20
deteriorating finances of PG&E Corp. PCG, news, msgs) unit Pacific Gas &=20
Electric Co. and Edison International (EIX, news, msgs) unit Southern=20
California Edison left them unable to purchase power for themselves.=20
The state's idea was to sign lots of long-term deals, thus locking in=20
supplies and bringing down spot-market prices by reducing the level of pani=
c=20
buying at the last minute. The hope was also that by spreading out the cost=
=20
of power over several years, the state could secure the electricity it need=
s=20
without raising consumers' rates.=20
Those hopes are unlikely to be realized. As reported, California state=20
Treasurer Phil Angelides has said a planned $10 billion municipal bond issu=
e=20
- the largest in U.S. history - will only cover the state's power purchases=
=20
through September if prices stay where they are. The California Department =
of=20
Water Resources, which is handling the state's power purchases, has already=
=20
spent about $3 billion on power, a total that is growing by about $45 milli=
on=20
a day.=20
California lawmakers and regulators are increasingly saying consumers' rate=
s=20
will have to rise to cover the cost of power bought on their behalf.=20
The West, heavily dependent on hydropower, is having one of its driest year=
s=20
on record. A number of officials and analysts see blackouts as a certainty=
=20
this summer, as California comes up short in its scramble for power.=20
-By Andrew Dowell, Dow Jones Newswires; 201-938-4430;=20

